i          ---------- Defining Terms ---------- 		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
0[1] Magick	/Magick (Thelema)	gopherpedia.com	70
i		gopher.black	70
iThe addition of the k to the end of magic has long been credited		gopher.black	70
ito Aleister Crowley's Thelema to differentiate the occult practice		gopher.black	70
ifrom stage magic and illusion. Since he coined the term I'll use		gopher.black	70
ihis definition here: "the Science and Art of causing Change to		gopher.black	70
ioccur in conformity with Will".		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iHis definition was quite loose, and if you read his works you'll		gopher.black	70
isee he uses the term interchangably to describe mundane acts, such		gopher.black	70
ias like reaching out and picking up a pencil, along side ritual		gopher.black	70
imagic which normally springs to mind. The idea that will can cause		gopher.black	70
iany change in an object that it would be normally capable of in		gopher.black	70
inature is not surprising, then. With the right effort, anything		gopher.black	70
ican be achieved. This line of thinking conflates and contrasts the		gopher.black	70
iconcepts of free will with destiny and leads to some... creative		gopher.black	70
iconclusions.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iFor the purposes of this post I'm going to narrow Crowley's focus		gopher.black	70
iinto just his later category of occult action of will to affect		gopher.black	70
ichange. I suspect this is where christyotwisty was going with her		gopher.black	70
iquestion. As we proceed I'll try to further narrow this definition		gopher.black	70
iand cross-reference it with other, similar concepts.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iFrequency illusion		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iAs defined on Wikipedia's list of cognative biases: "The illusion		gopher.black	70
iin which a word, a name, or other thing that has recently come to		gopher.black	70
ione's attention suddenly seems to appear with improbable frequency		gopher.black	70
ishortly afterwards (not to be confused with the recency illusion		gopher.black	70
ior selection bias). This illusion is sometimes referred to as the		gopher.black	70
iBaader-Meinhof phenomenon."		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iIn addition to this specific illusion bias, I'll also try to		gopher.black	70
iaddress synchronicity and confirmation bias. There's really a host		gopher.black	70
iof mental phenomena which are all interrelated in the context of		gopher.black	70
ithe question.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
i       ---------- Subject-matter clarification  ----------		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iBefore addressing the question directly I think I should say		gopher.black	70
ia word or two about the subject of magick itself. There is		gopher.black	70
ia strong divide between groups of people who entertain the idea of		gopher.black	70
imagick as a serious phenomenon and those who dismiss it as		gopher.black	70
ichildish delusion. All too often, the former group is then		gopher.black	70
istigmatized and preconceived prejudices run wild, which		gopher.black	70
iunfortunately make serious discussion all but impossible.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iI want to disuade that behavior by stretching the concept of		gopher.black	70
imagick to include similar practices that fall under more widely		gopher.black	70
iacceptable terminology. Remembering our core definition of		gopher.black	70
imagick--the use of will via occult (or paranormal) means to affect		gopher.black	70
ichange--we can find many common practices that fit the mold.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iFrom the East:		gopher.black	70
0[2] Qigong	/Qigong	gopherpedia.com	70
0[3] Tai Chi	/Tai Chi	gopherpedia.com	70
i		gopher.black	70
iThe entire system of Chinese medicine falls into this category,		gopher.black	70
imanipulating unseen energies through will and the use of natural		gopher.black	70
iactions, herbs, and meditation. Falun Gong, Prana, Tao Yin and so		gopher.black	70
ion also fit.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iFrom the West:		gopher.black	70
0[4] Laying on of hands	/Laying on of hands	gopherpedia.com	70
0[5] Exercism	/Exercism	gopherpedia.com	70
0[6] Hypnosis	/Hypnosis	gopherpedia.com	70
i		gopher.black	70
iIn the west there are many religious practices deeply rooted in		gopher.black	70
iChristianity which clearly fit the definition of magick we're		gopher.black	70
iusing. Between the extremes of popular religious rites and the		gopher.black	70
iridiculed parlor ritual there is a whole range of activity. Yoga,		gopher.black	70
ireiki, mindfullness medititation, and good old basic prayer all		gopher.black	70
iseek to affect some sort of change through the focus of primarily		gopher.black	70
imental expressions of will.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iAs you can see, the question here is not limited to casting spells		gopher.black	70
iin a circle under a full moon. You could reasonably reword		gopher.black	70
ichristyotwisty's question:		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
i  Those who pray for change: what tells you it's working and not		gopher.black	70
i  just your mind playing a trick on you?		gopher.black	70
